<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/14715a39c99dcc283ae3e6daf095af9e> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "De kŏmungo is een liggende houten citer met zes zijden snaren en wordt met een staafvormig, houten plectrum bespeeld. De klankkast is vervaardigd van paulowniahout. Drie van de snaren worden ondersteund door vaste bruggen, de overige drie door verplaatsbare bruggen (anjok). Dit instrument wordt als moeilijker bepeelbaar geacht dan de kayagŭm, de 12-snarige citer met alleen losse bruggen. Het instrument wordt in diverse genres gebruikt, van hofmuziek (a'ak) tot sjamanistische muziek (shinawi).\r\n\r\nThe kŏmungo has been treated courteously as one of the most important stringed instrument. The invention of this instrument is credited by the premier Wang san-ak of the Koguryŏ period. When he was playing the kŏmungo, a black crane flew near and danced to his playing, according to a historical book, samkuk-sagi. Many scholars assert themself that named the kŏmungo, refers to the colour and translates to \"black crane zither\" sometime.\r\nIt has six strings made of twisted thick silk threads. And they are rested on a wooden board which is made of a paulownia tree. The second, third and fourth strings from performer are held up by sixteen graduated props called as kwae in Korean, and the first, fifth and sixth strings from performer are supported by movable bridges shaped like a foot of a crane or wild goose's foot called as anjok in Korean. \r\nThe fine tuning of the strings is executed by sultae, a plectrum made of sea-bamboo at the bottom of the instrument, and the first, fifth and sixth may additionally be held-up by shifting the movable bridges to the left or right. The posture of playing is sitting cross-legged putting the right-leg underneath the left-knee first and put the upper part of a kŏmungo on the right-knee holding a kŏmungo erect in prop the reverse side of a kŏmungo up with left-knee and scrape taemo(upper side) of a geomungo with sultae(plectrum in Korean) in the right-hand, putting a geomungo in tune with left hand simultaneously. The kŏmungo is considered as an ideal instrument for displaying a player's technical skills and for expressing has/her feelings. These sprits are well embodied in such musics as sanjo and shinawi." .
